by Tatiana Bibikova¶

I'm going to explore the flights datasets.

My interest in exploring these dataset is to find out what are the characteristics of the cancelled flights. I would also like to check if it is changing over a years but I will start with couple of dataset as a sample and then will arrange a dataset from all the avaliable sets in the period from 1987 to 2008.¶

Univariate Exploration¶

As the name of the section states, I'm going to check if there any relation between cancelled flight and variables we have in the dataset, i.e. day of the week, day of the months, month, time, destination, origin, etc

Let's see what is the most common reason of cancellation¶
In [27]:
code = ['Carrier', 'Nas', 'Weather', 'Security']
ticks_loc = np.arange(0, 5, 1)
sb.countplot(data = cancel_2, x = 'CancellationCode'); #1987 dataset has no info 
plt.xticks(ticks_loc, code);
plt.title('Cancellation codes - year 2008');
most common reasons for cancellation are carrier and weather, while there are only 12 cases of security cancellation which makes it 0.008% of cases (at least in 2008)¶
In [28]:
base_color_1 = sb.color_palette()[0]

how day of the week and month affects cancellation¶

In [29]:

fridays remain the day of the week with wth most cancelled flights both in 1990 and 2008, while there are more cancelled flights on sundays in comparison to saturdays in 2008 than in 1990. will be interesting to have a look at the trend through the years¶

From univariate exploration and comparison of two years we can see some relations. fligths often being cancelled because if weather and there more during winter time.¶

day of the month or time of the days don't show any specific tendency as well as lenght of the flight. however size of the aiport and the time it's been operating might be a valid reason for higher amount of cancelled flights.¶

I adjusted initial datasets as my partuclar point of interest were cancelled flights so I removed unrelated information.¶

To be able to pring some histograms I got to delete entries with NaN values, however it was very low amount whihc won't affect the whole picture.¶

In some cases I got to calculate proportion as absolute amount wouldn't be representative enough.¶

Bivariate Exploration¶

as we've seen in univariate exploration, winter months have higher amount of cancellation, so we start at looking at those two variables - cause of cancellation and month¶

In [71]:
plt.figure(figsize = [15, 6])

as we can see on the graph weather is the leading cancellation reason in winter months which makes sence. that also means that origins with more distinct seasonal differences will have higher cancellation percentage¶

so we check the origin and cancellation code relations¶
